Don has played drum set and congas with a lengthy list of jazz and popular artists, including ... Paul Simon.", "doc_title": "Don Alias interviewed by Monk Rowe, New York City, New York, January 6, 2002", "collection": "hamilton", "url": "https://litsdigital.hamilton.edu/collections/object/don-alias-interviewed-monk-rowe-new-york-city-new-york-january-6-2002"}, {"speaker": "Rob Mounsey", "relation": "collaborated with", "confidence": 1.0, "evidence": "Paul and Roy Halee asked me... I finally did an arrangement for a Paul Simon record.", "doc_title": "Rob Mounsey interviewed by Monk Rowe, via Zoom, April 9, 2025", "collection": "hamilton", "url": "https://litsdigital.hamilton.edu/collections/object/rob-mounsey-interviewed-monk-rowe-zoom-april-9-2025"}, {"speaker": "Warren Bernhardt", "relation": "collaborated with", "confidence": 0.95, "evidence": "And I got to play with Vincent Nguini and Bakithi Kumalo with Paul Simon, you know, the “Graceland” guys and stuff... And then he’d turn it off as soon as you get two bars into it then the click was gone... But with Paul it’s like an art. We rehearsed that day... For Steely Dan I was the musical dir", "doc_title": "Warren Bernhardt interviewed by Monk Rowe, Bearsville, New York, January 3, 2012", "collection": "hamilton", "url": "https://litsdigital.hamilton.edu/collections/object/warren-bernhardt-interviewed-monk-rowe-bearsville-new-york-january-3-2012"}, {"speaker": "Toots Thielemans", "relation": "collaborated with", "confidence": 0.95, "evidence": "I had played at that time with Paul Simon... I was doing... there was a concert with Quincy... Paul, from what I understand, noticed me with Quincy, and that’s how I got the rehearsal… the call... Paul loved you.", "doc_title": "Toots Thielemans — Smithsonian Jazz Oral History", "collection": "si", "url": "https://americanhistory.si.edu/sites/default/files/file-uploader/Toots%20Thielemans%20Interview%20Transcription%20%282%29.pdf"}, {"speaker": "Tom Malone", "relation": "collaborated with", "confidence": 0.95, "evidence": "“Late in the Evening” by Paul Simon from the movie ... I did not get credit on the album, but it was the best big band I ever played with in New York.", "doc_title": "Tom Malone interviewed by Monk Rowe, via Zoom, May 3, 2023", "collection": "hamilton", "url": "https://litsdigital.hamilton.edu/collections/object/tom-malone-interviewed-monk-rowe-zoom-may-3-2023"}, {"speaker": "Dave Robinson", "relation": "knows of", "confidence": 0.9, "evidence": "[INTERVIEWER] It just popped into my head, do you include — you know Paul Simon did that song called “You Can Call Me Al”? [INTERVIEWEE] Right. That was Ronnie Cuber on his one and only appearance on bass sax.", "doc_title": "Dave Robinson interviewed by Monk Rowe, New York City, New York, January 13, 2007", "collection": "hamilton", "url": "https://litsdigital.hamilton.edu/collections/object/dave-robinson-interviewed-monk-rowe-new-york-city-new-york-january-13-2007"}]}